# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: css-virginia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] On August 22, 1851, *America* won the Royal Yacht Squadron's 53-mile (85 km) regatta around the Isle of Wight by 18 minutes.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The Squadron's "One Hundred Sovereign Cup" or "£100 Cup", sometimes mistakenly known in America as the "One Hundred Guinea Cup", was later renamed after the original winning yacht.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] A syndicate of New York Yacht Club members, headed by NYYC charter member Commodore John Cox Stevens, with members Edwin A.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Stevens, George Schuyler, Hamilton Wilkes, and J.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Beekman Finley, built a yacht to sail to England.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The purpose of this visit was twofold: to show off U.S. shipbuilding skill and make money through competing in yachting regattas.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Stevens employed the services of the shipyard of William H.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Brown and his chief designer, George Steers.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She was launched on May 3, 1851, from the Brown shipyard, near Eleventh Street, East River, New York.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Crewed by Brown and eight professional sailors, with George Steers, his older brother James, and James' son George as passengers, *America* left New York on June 21, 1851, and arrived at Le Havre on July 11.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] They were joined there by Commodore Stevens.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] After drydocking and repainting *America* left for Cowes, Isle of Wight, on July 30.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] While there the crew enjoyed the hospitality of the Royal Yacht Squadron while Stevens searched for someone who would race against his yacht.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The British yachting community had been following the construction of *America* with interest and perhaps some trepidation.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] When *America* arrived on the Solent on July 31 there was one yacht, *Laverock*, that appeared for an impromptu race.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The accounts of the race are contradictory: a British newspaper said *Laverock* held her own, but Stevens later reported that *America* beat her handily.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Whatever the outcome, it seemed to have discouraged other British yachtsmen from challenging *America* to a match.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She never raced until the last day of the Royal Yacht Squadron's annual members-only regatta for which Queen Victoria customarily donated the prize.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Because of *America*'s presence, a special provision was made to "open to all nations" a race of 53 miles (85 km) 'round the Isle of Wight, with no reservation for time allowance.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The race was held on August 22, 1851, with a 10:00 AM start for a line of seven schooners and another line of eight cutters.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] *America* had a slow start due to a fouled anchor and was well behind when she finally got under way.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Within half an hour however, she was in 5th place and gaining.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The eastern shoals of the Isle of Wight are called the Nab Rocks.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Traditionally, races would sail around the east (seaward) side of the lightship that marked the edge of the shoal, but one could sail between the lightship and the mainland if they had a knowledgeable pilot.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] *America* had such a pilot and he took her down the west (landward) side of the lightship.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] After the race a contestant protested this action, but was overruled because the official race rules did not specify on which side of the lightship a boat had to pass.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] This tactic put *America* in the lead, which she held throughout the rest of the race.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] At one point the jib boom broke due to a crew error, but it was replaced in fifteen minutes.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] On the final leg of the race the yacht *Aurora* closed but was 18 minutes behind when *America* finished shortly after 6:00 PM.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] John Cox Stevens and the syndicate from the New York Yacht Club owned the *America* from the time that she was launched on May 3, 1851, until ten days after she won the regatta that made her famous.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] On September 1, 1851, the yacht was sold to John de Blaquiere, 4th Baron de Blaquiere.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In late July 1852, *America* ran aground at Portsmouth, Hampshire and was damaged.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] De Blaquiere raced her only a few times before selling her in 1856 to Henry Montagu Upton, 2nd Viscount Templetown, who renamed her *Camilla* but failed to use or maintain her.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 1858, she was sold to Henry Sotheby Pitcher, a shipbuilder in Northfleet, Kent.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] He rebuilt *Camilla* and sold her to Henry Edward Decie in 1860, who brought her back to the United States.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Decie sold the ship to the Confederate States of America the same year for use as a blockade runner in the American Civil War, though he remained aboard as captain.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The yacht was renamed *Camilla* and carried Major Edward Clifford Anderson the Secretary of War in England, and Navy lieutenant James Heyward North on a secret mission to purchase weapons and supplies for the Confederacy, and to ascertain the loyalty of Captain Caleb Huse who was already in England.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Heyward was specifically tasked by Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Mallory to purchase ready built ironclad vessels.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] They departed Savannah, on May 22, 1861, running the blockade and arrived in Queesntown on June 22.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 1862, she was scuttled in Dunns Creek, north of Crescent City, Florida when Union troops took the city of Jacksonville.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She was raised, repaired, and renamed *America* by the Union and served the United States Navy on the blockade until May 1863.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She was armed with three smoothbore bronze cannon designed by John A.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Dahlgren and cast at the Washington Navy Yard.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] A 12-pounder was located on the bow and two 24-pounders were placed amidships.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She was assigned to the federal blockading squadron off Charleston, South Carolina, and was on patrol the night of March 19, 1863, when she spotted the smoke of a blockade runner near Dewees Inlet, South Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She immediately launched colored signal flares to alert the rest of the fleet.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The runner proved to be the CSS *Georgiana*, which was described as the most powerful Confederate cruiser then afloat.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] *America's* action ultimately resulted in the *Georgiana*'s wreck and destruction.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] *Georgiana* was the most important vessel to be captured or destroyed by the federal blockade.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 1863 *America* became a training ship at the United States Naval Academy.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] On August 8, 1870, the Navy entered her in the America's Cup race at New York Harbor, where she finished fourth.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 1923 *America* was given the hull designation of IX-41 by the US Navy.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] ("IX" being the designation for "unclassified miscellaneous".) She was not maintained at the Naval Academy either and became seriously decayed by 1940.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The shed which housed *America* collapsed during a heavy snowstorm on March 29, 1942.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The remains of the shed and ship were scrapped and burned in 1945.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The New York Yacht Club acquired several relics from *America* after her destruction.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] These include her transom eagle, rudder post and one of her masts.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The mast serves as the flag pole for the club's summer station in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The first replica of *America* was built by Goudy & Stevens Shipyard in Boothbay, Maine, and launched in 1967.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] She was built for Rudolph Schaefer Jr., owner of F. & M.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Construction was supervised by her first skipper, Newfoundland born Capt.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] A second replica of *America* was built in 1995 by Scarano Boatbuilding of Albany, NY for Ray Giovannoni and was operated by him for commercial events until his death.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] It had several modifications from the original design including widening the beam by 4 feet to accommodate interior layouts.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The original design had only one lantern (skylight) so three were added to bring light into the interior of the yacht.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] The yacht spent several years in Key West Florida and operated between Key West and New York City seasonally for the company Classic Harbor Line.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 2006 she was purchased by Troy Sears' company, Next Level Sailing, and her home port was moved to San Diego, California.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 2007 America was invited to Spain to help promote America's Cup racing and she was exhibited in June 2011 in San Francisco Bay in concert with exploratory preparations by the Oracle Racing team for the 2013 America's Cup race, which was held within the bay.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] In 2015 and 2016 she toured both US coasts and the Caribbean, again to promote America's Cup racing.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] During the interim and since then she has run whale watching and charter trips out of San Diego.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] A third replica was built in Varna, Bulgaria in 2005.
[src:css-virginia/america-yacht] Christened *Skythia*, the boat's home port later was Rostock, Germany, where she was used for commercial charter.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The **American Civil War Museum** is a multi-site museum in the Greater Richmond Region of central Virginia, dedicated to the history of the American Civil War.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The museum operates three sites: The White House of the Confederacy, the American Civil War Museum at Historic Tredegar in Richmond, and the American Civil War Museum at Appomattox.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] It maintains a comprehensive collection of artifacts, manuscripts, Confederate books and pamphlets, and photographs.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In November 2013, the Museum of the Confederacy and the American Civil War Center at Tredegar merged, creating the American Civil War Museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Its current name was announced in January 2014.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The Museum of the Confederacy was founded in 1894.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] It is located in the house that served as the White House of the Confederacy, two blocks north of the Virginia State Capitol, which the Ladies Hollywood Memorial Association saved from destruction.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] It opened as the Confederate Museum and White House of the Confederacy on February 22, 1896, the anniversary of Jefferson Davis's inauguration.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The house was named a National Historic Landmark in 1963 and Virginia Historic Landmark in 1966.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] A new building next door was built in 1976 for the expanding collection (and a 12-year restoration of the building began).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In 2006, museum officials announced that neither the museum nor the building would be moved.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In 2017, the location became a part of the American Civil War Museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] It maintains a collection of flags, weapons, documents, and personal effects related to the Confederacy, and offers tours of the home restored to its 1861–65 appearance.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The museum houses more than 15,000 documents and artifacts along with 500 original, wartime, battle flags from the Confederate States of America.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Among the thousands of other important pieces found there are items owned by Jefferson Davis, Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Johnston, John Bell Hood, Stonewall Jackson, Simon Bolivar Buckner, J.E.B.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Stuart, Joseph Wheeler, Wade Hampton, Lewis Armistead, and Raphael Semmes.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The provisional Confederate Constitution and the Great Seal of the Confederacy are also housed there.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] A newer building to better preserve and exhibit the museum's collections was built and opened in 1976 adjacent to the White House, on its remaining 0.75-acre (3,000 m2) property.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The anchor of the first ironclad warship, CSS *Virginia*, which fought the USS *Monitor* in the Battle of Hampton Roads on March 9, 1862, was displayed in front of the museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The White House of the Confederacy was closed in 1976, to be restored to its wartime appearance.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The restoration project was completed in 1988, and it reopened for public tours in June 1988.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The White House featured extensive reproduction wall coverings and draperies, as well as significant numbers of original White House furnishings from the Civil War period.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Lee: The Exhibition*; *The Confederate Navy*; and *Virginia and the Confederacy: A Quadricentennial Perspective*.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The Museum of the Confederacy was founded by Richmond's society ladies, starting with Isabel Maury, who was later joined by Ann Crenshaw Grant and Isobel Stewart Bryan.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Isabel Maury was the founder of the Museum of the Confederacy but she also was the first Regent of the Confederate Memorial Literary Society (CMLS).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The Isabel Maury Planned Giving Society continues the work of Mrs.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Isabel Maury, daughter of Robert Henry Maury, who, with the Relics Committee, was instrumental in securing much of the museum's collection.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] By the centennial anniversary of the Civil War, the museum's governing board determined that it wanted to see the museum evolve from a shrine to a more modern museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In 1963, the CMLS hired its first museum professional as executive director, and in 1970, changed the name of the institution to "The Museum of the Confederacy." Visitors peaked at 91,000 per year in the early 1990s but were down to around 51,000 in the early 2000s.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The White House of the Confederacy is a gray stuccoed neoclassical mansion built in 1818 by John Brockenbrough, who was president of the Bank of Virginia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Designed by Robert Mills, Brockenbrough's private residence was built in early nineteenth century on East Clay Street in Richmond's affluent Shockoe Hill neighborhood (later known as the Court End District), and was two blocks north of the Virginia State Capitol.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] President of the Confederate States of America Jefferson Davis, his wife Varina, and their children moved into the house in August 1861, and lived there for the remainder of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] President Davis maintained an at-home office on the second floor of the White House due to his poor health.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The house was abandoned during the evacuation of Richmond on April 2, 1865.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Within twelve hours, soldiers from Major General Godfrey Weitzel's XVIII Corps seized the former Confederate White House, intact.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] During his tour of Richmond, President Abraham Lincoln visited Davis's former residence, and it was where Union officers held a number of meetings with local officials in the aftermath.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] During Reconstruction, the building served as part of the headquarters for Military District Number One (Virginia), and was occasionally used as the residence of the commanding officer of the Department of Virginia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Following the end of Reconstruction, the House became a school—the Richmond Central School.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] When the city announced its plans to demolish the building to make way for a more modern school building in 1890, the Confederate Memorial Literary Society was formed with the purpose of saving the White House from destruction.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The museum is situated on eight acres of land and contains 5,000 square feet for exhibits.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The location changed its name in 2017 as part of the transition into the American Civil War Museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Historic Tredegar, home to The American Civil War Museum, traces its roots to 1836, when Francis B.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] He named his Richmond plant for a Welsh town and iron works.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In 1841 Deane hired Joseph Reid Anderson as commercial sales agent.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Under Joseph Reid Anderson's ownership, Tredegar manufactured an array of items including locomotives, train wheels, spikes, cables, ships, boilers, naval hardware, iron machinery, and brass items.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] In 2019, the museum completed a major new building on the site of the Tredegar Iron Works in downtown Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] The new building features more than 7,000 square feet of new gallery space for permanent and changing exhibitions of items from the museum's renowned collections of Civil War artifacts.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] An “immersion theater” highlighting Richmond's role in the war is still under construction.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Several prominent Civil War historians have had connections to the museum.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Douglas Southall Freeman, the biographer of George Washington and Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Thomas, and Harvard University President Drew Gilpin Faust have all done research there.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Robertson Jr., of Virginia Tech; Edwin C.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Bearss, Historian Emeritus of the National Park Service; and William J.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-museum] Cooper Jr. of LSU have each served as members of the museum's governing board.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:css-virginia/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] Arcadia Publishing was founded in Dover, New Hampshire, in 1993 by United Kingdom-based Tempus Publishing, but became independent after being acquired by its CEO in 2004.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] The corporate office is in Mount Pleasant, South Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] It has a catalog of more than 12,000 titles, and it—along with its subsidiary, The History Press—publishes 900 new titles every year.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] Its formula for regional publishing is to use local writers or historians to write about their community using 180 to 240 black-and-white photographs with captions and introductory paragraphs in a 128-page book.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] The *Images of America* series is the company's largest product line.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] Other series include *Images of Rail, Images of Sports, Images of Baseball, Black America, Postcard History, Campus History, Corporate History, Legendary Locals, Images of Modern America*, and *Then & Now*.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] In May 2017, Arcadia acquired Palmetto Publishing Group, a Charleston-based self-publishing service that had been in business since 2015.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] In 2018, Arcadia was acquired by Lezen, a new company owned by Lili and Michael Lynton.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] In March 2019, Walter Isaacson became the editor-at-large and senior adviser for Arcadia Publishing, where he will be promoting books for the company as well as editing, new strategy development, and partnerships.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] In 2010, Arcadia became the first major publisher to print all of their books on Forest Stewardship Council (FSC) paper.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] All of the publisher's books are also printed and manufactured in South Carolina on American-made paper.
[src:css-virginia/arcadia-publishing] The books are printed in the United States.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The **Atlantic Ocean** is the second largest of the world's five oceanic divisions, with an area of about 85,133,000 square kilometers (32,870,000 sq mi).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] It covers approximately 17% of Earth's surface and about 24% of its water surface area.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, it was known for separating the New World of the Americas (North America and South America) from the Old World of Afro-Eurasia (Africa, Asia, and Europe).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Through its separation of Afro-Eurasia from the Americas, the Atlantic Ocean has played a central role in the development of human society, globalization, and the histories of many nations.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the Norse were the first known humans to cross the Atlantic, it was the expedition of Christopher Columbus in 1492 that proved to be the most consequential.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Columbus's expedition ushered in an age of exploration and colonization of the Americas by European powers, most notably Portugal, Spain, France, and the United Kingdom.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] From the 16th to 19th centuries, the Atlantic Ocean was the center of both an eponymous slave trade and the Columbian exchange while occasionally hosting naval battles.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Such naval battles, as well as growing trade from regional American powers like the United States and Brazil, both increased in degree during the early 20th century.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] After World War II, major military operations became rarer, though notable postwar conflicts include the Cuban Missile Crisis and the Falklands War.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ocean remains a core component of trade around the world.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean's temperatures vary by location.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the South Atlantic maintains warm temperatures year-round, as its basin countries are tropical.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic maintains a temperate climate, as its basin countries are temperate and have seasons of extremely low temperatures and high temperatures.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean occupies an elongated, S-shaped basin extending longitudinally between Europe and Africa to the east, and the Americas to the west.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] As one component of the interconnected World Ocean, it is connected in the north to the Arctic Ocean, to the Pacific Ocean in the southwest, the Indian Ocean in the southeast, and the Southern Ocean in the south.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other definitions describe the Atlantic as extending southward to Antarctica.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is divided in two parts, the northern and southern Atlantic, by the Equator.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest known mentions of an "Atlantic" sea come from Stesichorus around mid-sixth century BC (Sch.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] 211): *Atlantikôi pelágei* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντικῷ πελάγει, 'the Atlantic sea', etym.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] 'Sea of Atlas') and in *The Histories* of Herodotus around 450 BC (Hdt.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] 1.202.4): *Atlantis thalassa* (Ancient Greek: Ἀτλαντὶς θάλασσα, 'Sea of Atlas' or 'the Atlantic sea'), where the name refers to "the sea beyond the pillars of Hercules" (the Strait of Gibraltar), beyond the Atlas Mountains in Morocco and off the West African coast.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In these uses, the name refers to Atlas, the Titan in Greek mythology, who supported the heavens and who later appeared as a frontispiece in medieval maps and atlases.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early Greek sailors believed the Atlantic to be part of the Oceanus, the great sea or river that surrounds all land, mentioned in ancient Greek mythological literature such as the *Iliad* and *Odyssey*.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This was in contrast to the enclosed seas well known to the Greeks, the Mediterranean and the Black Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The great ocean was believed to stretch around Africa, leading to the term "**Aethiopian Ocean**", derived from Ancient Ethiopia, applied to the southern Atlantic as late as the mid-19th century.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Age of Discovery, the Atlantic was also known to English cartographers as the **Great Western Ocean**.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The International Hydrographic Organization (IHO) defined the limits of the oceans and seas in 1953, but some of these definitions have been revised since then and some are not recognized by various authorities, institutions, and countries, such as the CIA World Factbook, for example.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Correspondingly, the extent and number of oceans and seas vary.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is bounded on the west by North and South America.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] It connects to the Arctic Ocean through the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, Greenland Sea, Norwegian Sea and Barents Sea with the northern divider passing through Iceland and Svalbard.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] To the east, the boundaries of the ocean proper are Europe and Africa: the Strait of Gibraltar (where it connects with the Mediterranean Sea – one of its marginal seas – and, in turn, the Black Sea, both of which also touch upon Asia).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southeast, the Atlantic merges into the Indian Ocean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The 20° East meridian, running south from Cape Agulhas to Antarctica defines its border.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the 1953 definition it extends south to Antarctica, while in later maps it is bounded at the 60° parallel by the Southern Ocean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic has irregular coasts indented by numerous bays, gulfs and seas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] These include the Baltic Sea, Black Sea, Caribbean Sea, Davis Strait, Denmark Strait, part of the Drake Passage, Gulf of Mexico, Labrador Sea, Mediterranean Sea, North Sea, Norwegian Sea, almost all of the Scotia Sea, and other tributary water bodies.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including these marginal seas the coast line of the Atlantic measures 111,866 km (69,510 mi) compared to 135,663 km (84,297 mi) for the Pacific.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Including its marginal seas, the Atlantic covers an area of 106,460,000 km2 (41,100,000 sq mi) or 23.5% of the global ocean and has a volume of 310,410,900 km3 (74,471,500 cu mi) or 23.3% of the total volume of the Earth's oceans.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The average depth is 3,646 m (11,962 ft) and the maximum depth, the Milwaukee Deep in the Puerto Rico Trench, is 8,376 m (27,480 ft).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The bathymetry of the Atlantic is dominated by a submarine mountain range called the Mid-Atlantic Ridge (MAR).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] It runs from 87°N or 300 km (190 mi) south of the North Pole to the subantarctic Bouvet Island at 54°S.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Expeditions to explore the bathymertry of the Atlantic include the *Challenger* expedition and the German *Meteor* expedition; as of 2001, Columbia University's Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and the United States Navy Hydrographic Office conduct research on the ocean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR divides the Atlantic longitudinally into two halves, in each of which a series of basins are delimited by secondary, transverse ridges.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR reaches above 2,000 m (6,600 ft) along most of its length, but is interrupted by larger transform faults at two places: the Romanche Trench near the Equator and the Gibbs fracture zone at 53°N.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is a barrier for bottom water, but at these two transform faults deep water currents can pass from one side to the other.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR rises 2–3 km (1.2–1.9 mi) above the surrounding ocean floor and its rift valley is the divergent boundary between the North American and Eurasian plates in the North Atlantic and the South American and African plates in the South Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR produces basaltic volcanoes in Eyjafjallajökull, Iceland, and pillow lava on the ocean floor.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The depth of water at the apex of the ridge is less than 2,700 m (1,500 fathoms; 8,900 ft) in most places, while the bottom of the ridge is three times as deep.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MAR is intersected by two perpendicular ridges: the Azores–Gibraltar transform fault, the boundary between the Nubian and Eurasian plates, intersects the MAR at the Azores triple junction, on either side of the Azores microplate, near the 40°N.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] A much vaguer, nameless boundary, between the North American and South American plates, intersects the MAR near or just north of the Fifteen-Twenty fracture zone, approximately at 16°N.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The remainder of the ridge was discovered in the 1920s by the German *Meteor* expedition using echo-sounding equipment.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exploration of the MAR in the 1950s led to the general acceptance of seafloor spreading and plate tectonics.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Most of the MAR runs under water but where it reaches the surfaces it has produced volcanic islands.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Continental shelves in the Atlantic are wide off Newfoundland, southernmost South America, and northeastern Europe.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the western Atlantic carbonate platforms dominate large areas, for example, the Blake Plateau and Bermuda Rise.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic is surrounded by passive margins except at a few locations where active margins form deep trenches: the Puerto Rico Trench (8,376 m or 27,480 ft maximum depth) in the western Atlantic and South Sandwich Trench (8,264 m or 27,113 ft) in the South Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are numerous submarine canyons off northeastern North America, western Europe, and northwestern Africa.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Some of these canyons extend along the continental rises and farther into the abyssal plains as deep-sea channels.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1922, a historic moment in cartography and oceanography occurred.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The USS *Stewart* used a Navy Sonic Depth Finder to draw a continuous map across the bed of the Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This involved little guesswork because the idea of sonar is straightforward with pulses being sent from the vessel, which bounce off the ocean floor, then return to the vessel.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The deep ocean floor is thought to be fairly flat with occasional deeps, abyssal plains, trenches, seamounts, basins, plateaus, canyons, and some guyots.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various shelves along the margins of the continents constitute about 11% of the bottom topography with few deep channels cut across the continental rise.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The mean depth between 60°N and 60°S is 3,730 m (12,240 ft), or close to the average for the global ocean, with a modal depth between 4,000 and 5,000 m (13,000 and 16,000 ft).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the South Atlantic the Walvis Ridge and Rio Grande Rise form barriers to ocean currents.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Laurentian Abyss is found off the eastern coast of Canada.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Surface water temperatures, which vary with latitude, current systems, and season and reflect the latitudinal distribution of solar energy, range from below −2 °C (28 °F) to over 30 °C (86 °F).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum temperatures occur north of the equator, and minimum values are found in the polar regions.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the middle latitudes, the area of maximum temperature variations, values may vary by 7–8 °C (13–14 °F).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] From October to June the surface is usually covered with sea ice in the Labrador Sea, Denmark Strait, and Baltic Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Coriolis effect circulates North Atlantic water in a clockwise direction, whereas South Atlantic water circulates counter-clockwise.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The south tides in the Atlantic Ocean are semi-diurnal; that is, two high tides occur every 24 lunar hours.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In latitudes above 40° North some east–west oscillation, known as the North Atlantic oscillation, occurs.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] On average, the Atlantic is the saltiest major ocean; surface water salinity in the open ocean ranges from 33 to 37 parts per thousand (3.3–3.7%) by mass and varies with latitude and season.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Evaporation, precipitation, river inflow and sea ice melting influence surface salinity values.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Although the lowest salinity values are just north of the equator (because of heavy tropical rainfall), in general, the lowest values are in the high latitudes and along coasts where large rivers enter.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Maximum salinity values occur at about 25° north and south, in subtropical regions with low rainfall and high evaporation.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The high surface salinity in the Atlantic, on which the Atlantic thermohaline circulation is dependent, is maintained by two processes.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Agulhas Leakage/Rings brings salty Indian Ocean waters into the South Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] While the "Atmospheric Bridge" evaporates subtropical Atlantic waters and exports it to the Pacific.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean consists of four major, upper water masses with distinct temperature and salinity.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic subarctic upper water in the northernmost North Atlantic is the source for subarctic intermediate water and North Atlantic intermediate water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water can be divided into the eastern and western North Atlantic central water since the western part is strongly affected by the Gulf Stream and therefore the upper layer is closer to underlying fresher subpolar intermediate water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The eastern water is saltier because of its proximity to Mediterranean water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic central water flows into South Atlantic central water at 15°N.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] There are five intermediate waters: four low-salinity waters formed at subpolar latitudes and one high-salinity formed through evaporation.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Arctic intermediate water flows from the north to become the source for North Atlantic deep water, south of the Greenland-Scotland sill.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] These two intermediate waters have different salinity in the western and eastern basins.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The wide range of salinities in the North Atlantic is caused by the asymmetry of the northern subtropical gyre and a large number of contributions from a wide range of sources: Labrador Sea, Norwegian-Greenland Sea, Mediterranean, and South Atlantic Intermediate Water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Along its path across Earth the composition of the NADW is affected by other water masses, especially Antarctic bottom water and Mediterranean overflow water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW is fed by a flow of warm shallow water into the northern North Atlantic which is responsible for the anomalous warm climate in Europe.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Changes in the formation of NADW have been linked to global climate changes in the past.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Since human-made substances were introduced into the environment, the path of the NADW can be traced throughout its course by measuring tritium and radiocarbon from nuclear weapon tests in the 1960s and CFCs.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The clockwise warm-water North Atlantic Gyre occupies the northern Atlantic, and the counter-clockwise warm-water South Atlantic Gyre appears in the southern Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This system of currents transports warm water into the North Atlantic, without which temperatures in the North Atlantic and Europe would plunge dramatically.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] North of the North Atlantic Gyre, the cyclonic North Atlantic Subpolar Gyre plays a key role in climate variability.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is governed by ocean currents from marginal seas and regional topography, rather than being steered by wind, both in the deep ocean and at sea level.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The subpolar gyre forms an important part of the global thermohaline circulation.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Its eastern portion includes eddying branches of the North Atlantic Current which transport warm, saline waters from the subtropics to the northeastern Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] There this water is cooled during winter and forms return currents that merge along the eastern continental slope of Greenland where they form an intense (40–50 Sv) current which flows around the continental margins of the Labrador Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] A third of this water becomes part of the deep portion of the North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The NADW, in turn, feeds the meridional overturning circulation (MOC), the northward heat transport of which is threatened by anthropogenic climate change.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large variations in the subpolar gyre on a decade-century scale, associated with the North Atlantic oscillation, are especially pronounced in Labrador Sea Water, the upper layers of the MOC.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic is dominated by the anti-cyclonic southern subtropical gyre.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The South Atlantic Central Water originates in this gyre, while Antarctic Intermediate Water originates in the upper layers of the circumpolar region, near the Drake Passage and the Falkland Islands.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Both these currents receive some contribution from the Indian Ocean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] On the African east coast, the small cyclonic Angola Gyre lies embedded in the large subtropical gyre.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The southern subtropical gyre is partly masked by a wind-induced Ekman layer.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The residence time of the gyre is 4.4–8.5 years.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] North Atlantic Deep Water flows southward below the thermocline of the subtropical gyre.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Sargasso Sea in the western North Atlantic can be defined as the area where two species of *Sargassum* (*S. fluitans* and *natans*) float, an area 4,000 km (2,500 mi) wide and encircled by the Gulf Stream, North Atlantic Drift, and North Equatorial Current.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This population of seaweed probably originated from Tertiary ancestors on the European shores of the former Tethys Ocean and has, if so, maintained itself by vegetative growth, floating in the ocean for millions of years.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other species endemic to the Sargasso Sea include the sargassum fish, a predator with algae-like appendages which hovers motionless among the *Sargassum*.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Fossils of similar fishes have been found in fossil bays of the former Tethys Ocean, in what is now the Carpathian region, that were similar to the Sargasso Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] It is possible that the population in the Sargasso Sea migrated to the Atlantic as the Tethys closed at the end of the Miocene around 17 Ma.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The origin of the Sargasso fauna and flora remained enigmatic for centuries.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The fossils found in the Carpathians in the mid-20th century often called the "quasi-Sargasso assemblage", finally showed that this assemblage originated in the Carpathian Basin from where it migrated over Sicily to the central Atlantic where it evolved into modern species of the Sargasso Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The location of the spawning ground for European eels remained unknown for decades.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the early 19th century it was discovered that the southern Sargasso Sea is the spawning ground for both the European and American eel and that the former migrate more than 5,000 km (3,100 mi) and the latter 2,000 km (1,200 mi).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents such as the Gulf Stream transport eel larvae from the Sargasso Sea to foraging areas in North America, Europe, and northern Africa.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Recent but disputed research suggests that eels possibly use Earth's magnetic field to navigate through the ocean both as larvae and as adults.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The climate is influenced by the temperatures of the surface waters and water currents as well as winds.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Because of the ocean's great capacity to store and release heat, maritime climates are more moderate and have less extreme seasonal variations than inland climates.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Precipitation can be approximated from coastal weather data and air temperature from water temperatures.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oceans are the major source of atmospheric moisture that is obtained through evaporation.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Climatic zones vary with latitude; the warmest zones stretch across the Atlantic north of the equator.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The coldest zones are in high latitudes, with the coldest regions corresponding to the areas covered by sea ice.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Ocean currents influence the climate by transporting warm and cold waters to other regions.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The winds that are cooled or warmed when blowing over these currents influence adjacent land areas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream and its northern extension towards Europe, the North Atlantic Drift is thought to have at least some influence on climate.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] For example, the Gulf Stream helps moderate winter temperatures along the coastline of southeastern North America, keeping it warmer in winter along the coast than inland areas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gulf Stream also keeps extreme temperatures from occurring on the Florida Peninsula.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the higher latitudes, the North Atlantic Drift, warms the atmosphere over the oceans, keeping the British Isles and northwestern Europe mild and cloudy, and not severely cold in winter, like other locations at the same high latitude.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The cold water currents contribute to heavy fog off the coast of eastern Canada (the Grand Banks of Newfoundland area) and Africa's northwestern coast.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In general, winds transport moisture and air over land areas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Every winter, the Icelandic Low produces frequent storms.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Icebergs are common from early February to the end of July across the shipping lanes near the Grand Banks of Newfoundland.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The ice season is longer in the polar regions, but there is little shipping in those areas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Hurricanes are a hazard in the western parts of the North Atlantic during the summer and autumn.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Due to a consistently strong wind shear and a weak Intertropical Convergence Zone, South Atlantic tropical cyclones are rare.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Atlantic Ocean is underlain mostly by dense mafic oceanic crust made up of basalt and gabbro and overlain by fine clay, silt and siliceous ooze on the abyssal plain.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The continental margins and continental shelf mark lower density, but greater thickness felsic continental rock that is often much older than that of the seafloor.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The oldest oceanic crust in the Atlantic is up to 145 million years and is situated off the west coast of Africa and the east coast of North America, or on either side of the South Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In many places, the continental shelf and continental slope are covered in thick sedimentary layers.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, on the North American side of the ocean, large carbonate deposits formed in warm shallow waters such as Florida and the Bahamas, while coarse river outwash sands and silt are common in shallow shelf areas like the Georges Bank.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Coarse sand, boulders, and rocks were transported into some areas, such as off the coast of Nova Scotia or the Gulf of Maine during the Pleistocene ice ages.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The break-up of Pangaea began in the central Atlantic, between North America and Northwest Africa, where rift basins opened during the Late Triassic and Early Jurassic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This period also saw the first stages of the uplift of the Atlas Mountains.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The exact timing is controversial with estimates ranging from 200 to 170 Ma.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Theoliitic dikes, sills, and lava flows from the CAMP eruption at 200 Ma have been found in West Africa, eastern North America, and northern South America.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The extent of the volcanism has been estimated to 4.5×106 km2 (1.7×106 sq mi) of which 2.5×106 km2 (9.7×105 sq mi) covered what is now northern and central Brazil.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the Central American Isthmus closed the Central American Seaway at the end of the Pliocene 2.8 Ma ago.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The formation of the isthmus resulted in the migration and extinction of many land-living animals, known as the Great American Interchange, but the closure of the seaway resulted in a "Great American Schism" as it affected ocean currents, salinity, and temperatures in both the Atlantic and Pacific.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Marine organisms on both sides of the isthmus became isolated and either diverged or went extinct.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologically, the North Atlantic is the area delimited to the south by two conjugate margins, Newfoundland and Iberia, and to the north by the Arctic Eurasian Basin.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic closely followed the margins of its predecessor, the Iapetus Ocean, and spread from the central Atlantic in six stages: Iberia–Newfoundland, Porcupine–North America, Eurasia–Greenland, Eurasia–North America.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Active and inactive spreading systems in this area are marked by the interaction with the Iceland hotspot.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Seafloor spreading led to the extension of the crust and the formation of troughs and sedimentary basins.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Rockall Trough opened between 105 and 84 million years ago although the rift failed along with one leading into the Bay of Biscay.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spreading began opening the Labrador Sea around 61 million years ago, continuing until 36 million years ago.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Geologists distinguish two magmatic phases.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] One from 62 to 58 million years ago predates the separation of Greenland from northern Europe while the second from 56 to 52 million years ago happened as the separation occurred.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland began to form 62 million years ago due to a particularly concentrated mantle plume.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Large quantities of basalt erupted at this time period are found on Baffin Island, Greenland, the Faroe Islands, and Scotland, with ash falls in Western Europe acting as a stratigraphic marker.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The opening of the North Atlantic caused a significant uplift of continental crust along the coast.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] For instance, despite 7 km thick basalt, Gunnbjorn Field in East Greenland is the highest point on the island, elevated enough that it exposes older Mesozoic sedimentary rocks at its base, similar to old lava fields above sedimentary rocks in the uplifted Hebrides of western Scotland.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The North Atlantic Ocean contains about 810 seamounts, most of them situated along the Mid-Atlantic Ridge.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The OSPAR database (Convention for the Protection of the Marine Environment of the North-East Atlantic) mentions 104 seamounts: 74 within national exclusive economic zones.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Of these seamounts, 46 are located close to the Iberian Peninsula.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] West Gondwana (South America and Africa) broke up in the Early Cretaceous to form the South Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The apparent fit between the coastlines of the two continents was noted on the first maps that included the South Atlantic and it was also the subject of the first computer-assisted plate tectonic reconstructions in 1965.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This magnificent fit, however, has since then proven problematic and later reconstructions have introduced various deformation zones along the shorelines to accommodate the northward-propagating break-up.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Intra-continental rifts and deformations have also been introduced to subdivide both continental plates into sub-plates.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the southern segment the Early Cretaceous (133–130 Ma) intensive magmatism of the Paraná–Etendeka Large Igneous Province produced by the Tristan hotspot resulted in an estimated volume of 1.5×106 to 2.0×106 km3 (3.6×105 to 4.8×105 cu mi).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Dyke swarms in Brazil, Angola, eastern Paraguay, and Namibia, however, suggest the LIP originally covered a much larger area and also indicate failed rifts in all these areas.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Associated offshore basaltic flows reach as far south as the Falkland Islands and South Africa.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Traces of magmatism in both offshore and onshore basins in the central and southern segments have been dated to 147–49 Ma with two peaks between 143 and 121 Ma and 90–60 Ma.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the Falkland segment rifting began with dextral movements between the Patagonia and Colorado sub-plates between the Early Jurassic (190 Ma) and the Early Cretaceous (126.7 Ma).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Around 150 Ma sea-floor spreading propagated northward into the southern segment.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] No later than 130 Ma rifting had reached the Walvis Ridge–Rio Grande Rise.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In the central segment, rifting started to break Africa in two by opening the Benue Trough around 118 Ma.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Rifting in the central segment, however, coincided with the Cretaceous Normal Superchron (also known as the Cretaceous quiet period), a 40 Ma period without magnetic reversals, which makes it difficult to date sea-floor spreading in this segment.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The equatorial segment is the last phase of the break-up, but, because it is located on the Equator, magnetic anomalies cannot be used for dating.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Various estimates date the propagation of seafloor spreading in this segment and consequent opening of the Equatorial Atlantic Gateway (EAG) to the period 120–96 Ma.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This final stage, nevertheless, coincided with or resulted in the end of continental extension in Africa.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] About 50 Ma the opening of the Drake Passage resulted from a change in the motions and separation rate of the South American and Antarctic plates.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] First, small ocean basins opened and a shallow gateway appeared during the Middle Eocene.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] 34–30 Ma a deeper seaway developed, followed by an Eocene–Oligocene climatic deterioration and the growth of the Antarctic ice sheet.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] An embryonic subduction margin is potentially developing west of Gibraltar.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Gibraltar Arc in the western Mediterranean is migrating westward into the central Atlantic where it joins the converging African and Eurasian plates.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Together these three tectonic forces are slowly developing into a new subduction system in the eastern Atlantic Basin.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Meanwhile, the Scotia Arc and Caribbean plate in the western Atlantic Basin are eastward-propagating subduction systems that might, together with the Gibraltar system, represent the beginning of the closure of the Atlantic Ocean and the final stage of the Atlantic Wilson cycle.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other theories propose that the Atlantic will continue to widen while the Pacific Ocean closes first.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This would create the future supercontinent Amasia.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This theory states over the next 200 to 300 million years, dominant subduction in the Pacific will close the ocean while the Atlantic continues to get wider.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) studies indicate that 80,000–60,000 years ago a major demographic expansion within Africa, derived from a single, small population, coincided with the emergence of behavioral complexity and the rapid MIS 5–4 environmental changes.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This group of people not only expanded over the whole of Africa, but also started to disperse out of Africa into Asia, Europe, and Australasia around 65,000 years ago and quickly replaced the archaic humans in these regions.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the Last Glacial Maximum (LGM) 20,000 years ago humans had to abandon their initial settlements along the European North Atlantic coast and retreat to the Mediterranean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following rapid climate changes at the end of the LGM this region was repopulated by Magdalenian culture.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Other hunter-gatherers followed in waves interrupted by hazards such as the Laacher See volcanic eruption, the inundation of Doggerland (now the North Sea), and the formation of the Baltic Sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The European coasts of the North Atlantic were permanently populated about 9,000–8.5,000 years ago.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This human dispersal left abundant traces along the coasts of the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] 50 kya-old, deeply stratified shell middens found in Ysterfontein on the western coast of South Africa are associated with the Middle Stone Age (MSA).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The MSA population was small and dispersed and the rate of their reproduction and exploitation was less intense than those of later generations.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] While their middens resemble 12–11 kya-old Late Stone Age (LSA) middens found on every inhabited continent, the 50–45 kya-old Enkapune Ya Muto in Kenya probably represents the oldest traces of the first modern humans to disperse out of Africa.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The same development can be seen in Europe.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In La Riera Cave (23–13 kya) in Asturias, Spain, only some 26,600 molluscs were deposited over 10 kya.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In contrast, 8–7 kya-old shell middens in Portugal, Denmark, and Brazil generated thousands of tons of debris and artefacts.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Ertebølle middens in Denmark, for example, accumulated 2,000 m3 (71,000 cu ft) of shell deposits representing some 50 million molluscs over only a thousand years.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The earliest exploitation took place on the submerged shelves, now submerged and most settlements now excavated were then located several kilometers from these shelves.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The reduced quantities of shells in the lower levels can represent the few shells that were exported inland.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] During the LGM the Laurentide Ice Sheet covered most of northern North America while Beringia connected Siberia to Alaska.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1973, late American geoscientist Paul S.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Furthermore, colonisation models based on mtDNA, yDNA, and atDNA data respectively support neither the "blitzkrieg" nor the "three-wave" hypotheses but they also deliver mutually ambiguous results.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Contradictory data from archaeology and genetics will most likely deliver future hypotheses that will, eventually, confirm each other.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] A proposed route across the Pacific to South America could explain early South American finds and another hypothesis proposes a northern path, through the Canadian Arctic and down the North American Atlantic coast.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Early settlements across the Atlantic have been suggested by alternative theories, ranging from purely hypothetical to mostly disputed, including the Solutrean hypothesis and some of the Pre-Columbian trans-oceanic contact theories.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The Norse settlement of the Faroe Islands and Iceland began during the 9th and 10th centuries.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] A settlement on Greenland was established before 1000 CE, but contact with it was lost in 1409 and it was finally abandoned during the early Little Ice Age.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Iceland was initially settled 865–930 CE following a warm period when winter temperatures hovered around 2 °C (36 °F) which made farming favorable at high latitudes.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] This did not last, however, and temperatures quickly dropped; at 1080 CE summer temperatures had reached a maximum of 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The *Landnámabók* (*Book of Settlement*) records disastrous famines during the first century of settlement – "men ate foxes and ravens" and "the old and helpless were killed and thrown over cliffs" – and by the early 1200s hay had to be abandoned for short-season crops such as barley.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Christopher Columbus reached the Americas in 1492, sailing under the Spanish flag.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Six years later Vasco da Gama reached India under the Portuguese flag, by navigating south around the Cape of Good Hope, thus proving that the Atlantic and Indian Oceans are connected.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] In 1500, in his voyage to India following Vasco da Gama, Pedro Álvares Cabral reached Brazil, taken by the currents of the South Atlantic Gyre.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Following these explorations, Spain and Portugal quickly conquered and colonized large territories in the New World and forced the Amerindian population into slavery in order to exploit the vast quantities of silver and gold they found.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Spain and Portugal monopolized this trade in order to keep other European nations out, but conflicting interests nevertheless led to a series of Spanish-Portuguese wars.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] A peace treaty mediated by the Pope divided the conquered territories into Spanish and Portuguese sectors while keeping other colonial powers away.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] England, France, and the Dutch Republic enviously watched the Spanish and Portuguese wealth grow and allied themselves with pirates such as Henry Mainwaring and Alexandre Exquemelin.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] They could explore the convoys leaving the Americas because prevailing winds and currents made the transport of heavy metals slow and predictable.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Between the 15th century and 1888, when Brazil became the last part of the Americas to end the slave trade, an estimated 9.5 million enslaved Africans were shipped into the New World, most of them destined for agricultural labor.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] The slave trade was officially abolished in the British Empire and the United States in 1808, and slavery itself was abolished in the British Empire in 1838 and in the United States in 1865 after the Civil War.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] From Columbus to the Industrial Revolution trans-Atlantic trade, including colonialism and slavery, became crucial for Western Europe.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] For European countries with direct access to the Atlantic (including Britain, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and Spain) 1500–1800 was a period of sustained growth during which these countries grew richer than those in Eastern Europe and Asia.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Colonialism evolved as part of the trans-Atlantic trade, but this trade also strengthened the position of merchant groups at the expense of monarchs.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Growth was more rapid in non-absolutist countries, such as Britain and the Netherlands, and more limited in absolutist monarchies, such as Portugal, Spain, and France, where profit mostly or exclusively benefited the monarchy and its allies.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Trans-Atlantic trade also resulted in increasing urbanization: in European countries facing the Atlantic, urbanization grew from 8% in 1300, 10.1% in 1500, to 24.5% in 1850; in other European countries from 10% in 1300, 11.4% in 1500, to 17% in 1850.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] Likewise, GDP doubled in Atlantic countries but rose by only 30% in the rest of Europe.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p01] By the end of the 17th century, the volume of the Trans-Atlantic trade had surpassed that of the Mediterranean trade.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic has contributed significantly to the development and economy of surrounding countries.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Besides major transatlantic transportation and communication routes, the Atlantic offers abundant petroleum deposits in the sedimentary rocks of the continental shelves.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The Atlantic harbors petroleum and gas fields, fish, marine mammals (seals and whales), sand and gravel aggregates, placer deposits, polymetallic nodules, and precious stones.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Gold deposits are a mile or two underwater on the ocean floor, however, the deposits are also encased in rock that must be mined through.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Currently, there is no cost-effective way to mine or extract gold from the ocean to make a profit.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Various international treaties attempt to reduce pollution caused by environmental threats such as oil spills, marine debris, and the incineration of toxic wastes at sea.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The shelves of the Atlantic hosts one of the world's richest fishing resources.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The most productive areas include the Grand Banks of Newfoundland, the Scotian Shelf, Georges Bank off Cape Cod, the Bahama Banks, the waters around Iceland, the Irish Sea, the Bay of Fundy, the Dogger Bank of the North Sea, and the Falkland Banks.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The third group, "continuously increasing trend since 1950", is only found in the Indian Ocean and western Pacific.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Northeast Atlantic is schematically limited to the 40°00' west longitude (except around Greenland), south to the 36°00' north latitude, and to the 68°30' east longitude, with both the west and east longitude limits reaching to the north pole.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northeast Atlantic total catches decreased between the mid-1970s and the 1990s and reached 8.7 million tons in 2013.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached a 2.4 million tons peak in 2004 but was down to 628,000 tons in 2013.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Recovery plans for cod, sole, and plaice have reduced mortality in these species.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] reached its lowest levels in the 1960s–1980s but is now recovered.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] which has now recovered to fully fished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] and deep-water species difficult to assess but most likely they remain vulnerable to overfishing.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northeast Atlantic, 21% of stocks are considered overfished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Main fishing EU countries are Denmark, France, the Netherlands and Spain.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the Northwest Atlantic landings have decreased from 4.2 million tons in the early 1970s to 1.9 million tons in 2013.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Stocks of invertebrates, in contrast, remain at record levels of abundance.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] 31% of stocks are overfished in the northwest Atlantic.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In 1497, John Cabot became the first Western European since the Vikings to explore mainland North America and one of his major discoveries was the abundant resources of Atlantic cod off Newfoundland.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Referred to as "Newfoundland Currency" this discovery yielded some 200 million tons of fish over five centuries.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, new fisheries started to exploit haddock, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the introduction of European and Asian distant-water fleets in the area dramatically increased the fishing capacity and the number of exploited species.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] It also expanded the exploited areas from near-shore to the open sea and to great depths to include deep-water species such as redfish, Greenland halibut, witch flounder, and grenadiers.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Overfishing in the area was recognized as early as the 1960s but, because this was occurring on international waters, it took until the late 1970s before any attempts to regulate was made.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the early 1990s, this finally resulted in the collapse of the Atlantic northwest cod fishery.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The population of a number of deep-sea fishes also collapsed in the process, including American plaice, redfish, and Greenland halibut, together with flounder and grenadier.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] constitute about 50% of landings with sardine reaching 0.6–1.0 million tons per year.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Almost half of the stocks are fished at biologically unsustainable levels.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Total catches have been fluctuating since the 1970s; reaching 3.9 million tons in 2013 or slightly less than the peak production in 2010.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the western central-Atlantic, catches have been decreasing since 2000 and reached 1.3 million tons in 2013.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] , reached a million tons in the mid-1980s but only half a million tons in 2013 and is now considered fully fished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] was an important species in the 1990s but is now considered overfished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] are considered fully fished approaching overfished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] 44% of stocks are being fished at unsustainable levels.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the southeast Atlantic catches have decreased from 3.3 million tons in the early 1970s to 1.3 million tons in 2013.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] are the most important species, together representing almost half of the landings.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In the southwest Atlantic, a peak was reached in the mid-1980s and catches now fluctuate between 1.7 and 2.6 million tons.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] , which reached half a million tons in 2013 or half the peak value, is considered fully fished to overfished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] , with a production of 100,000 tons in 2013 it is now considered overfished.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Endangered marine species include the manatee, seals, sea lions, turtles, and whales.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Drift net fishing can kill dolphins, albatrosses and other seabirds (petrels, auks), hastening the fish stock decline and contributing to international disputes.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Marine pollution is a generic term for the entry into the ocean of potentially hazardous chemicals or particles.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The biggest culprits are rivers which carry many agricultural fertilizer chemicals as well as livestock and human waste.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The excess of oxygen-depleting chemicals leads to hypoxia and the creation of a dead zone.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Marine debris, which is also known as marine litter, describes human-created waste floating in a body of water.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Oceanic debris tends to accumulate at the center of gyres and coastlines, frequently washing aground where it is known as beach litter.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The North Atlantic garbage patch is estimated to be hundreds of kilometers across in size.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Other pollution concerns include agricultural and municipal waste.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] A USAF C-124 aircraft from Dover Air Force Base, Delaware was carrying three nuclear bombs over the Atlantic Ocean when it experienced a loss of power.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] For their own safety, the crew jettisoned two nuclear bombs, which were never recovered.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] North Atlantic hurricane activity has increased over past decades because of increased sea surface temperature (SST) at tropical latitudes, changes that can be attributed to either the natural Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) or to anthropogenic climate change.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] A 2005 report indicated that the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC) slowed down by 30% between 1957 and 2004.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] In 2024, the research highlighted a significant weakening of the AMOC by approximately 12% over the past two decades.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] If the AMO were responsible for SST variability, the AMOC would have increased in strength, which is apparently not the case.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Furthermore, it is clear from statistical analyses of annual tropical cyclones that these changes do not display multidecadal cyclicity.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] Therefore, these changes in SST must be caused by human activities.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] The ocean mixed layer plays an important role in heat storage over seasonal and decadal time scales, whereas deeper layers are affected over millennia and have a heat capacity about 50 times that of the mixed layer.
[src:css-virginia/atlantic-ocean-p02] This heat uptake provides a time-lag for climate change but it also results in thermal expansion of the oceans which contributes to sea level rise.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The **Battle of Hampton Roads**, also referred to as the **Battle of the *Monitor* and *Merrimack*** or the **Battle of Ironclads**, was a naval battle during the American Civil War.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was fought over two days, March 8 and 9, 1862, in Hampton Roads, a roadstead in Virginia where the Elizabeth and Nansemond rivers meet the James River just before it flows into Chesapeake Bay by the city of Norfolk.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle was a part of the effort of the Confederacy to break the Union blockade, which had cut off Virginia's largest cities and major industrial centers, Norfolk and Richmond, from international trade.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] This battle was significant in that it was the first combat between ironclad warships, the USS *Monitor* and CSS *Virginia*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate fleet consisted of the ironclad ram *Virginia* (built from remnants of the burned steam frigate USS *Merrimack*) and several supporting vessels.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the first day of battle, they were opposed by several conventional, wooden-hulled ships of the Union Navy.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On that day, the *Virginia* was able to destroy two ships of the Union flotilla, USS *Congress* and USS *Cumberland*, and was about to attack a third, USS *Minnesota*, which had run aground.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] However, the action was halted by darkness and falling tide, so *Virginia* retired to take care of her few wounded—which included her captain, Flag Officer Franklin Buchanan—and repair her minimal battle damage.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Determined to complete the destruction of *Minnesota*, Catesby ap Roger Jones, acting as captain in Buchanan's absence, returned the ship to the fray the next morning, March 9.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the night, however, the ironclad *Monitor* had arrived and had taken a position to defend *Minnesota*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] When *Virginia* approached, *Monitor* intercepted her.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The two ironclads fought for about three hours, with neither able to inflict significant damage on the other.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The duel ended indecisively, *Virginia* returning to her home at the Gosport Navy Yard for repairs and strengthening, and *Monitor* to her station defending *Minnesota*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The ships did not fight again, and the blockade remained in place.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle received worldwide attention, having immediate effects on navies around the world.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The preeminent naval powers, Great Britain and France, halted further construction of wooden-hulled ships, and others followed suit.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although Britain and France had been engaged in an iron-clad arms race since the 1830s, the Battle of Hampton Roads signaled a new age of naval warfare had arrived for the whole world.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] A new type of warship, monitor, was produced on the principle of the original.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of a small number of very heavy guns, mounted so that they could fire in all directions, was first demonstrated by *Monitor* but soon became standard in warships of all types.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Shipbuilders also incorporated rams into the designs of warship hulls for the rest of the century.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 19, 1861, shortly after the outbreak of hostilities at Charleston Harbor, US President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a blockade of ports in the seceded states.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On April 27, after Virginia and North Carolina had also passed ordinances of secession, the blockade was extended to include their ports also.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Even before the extension, local troops had seized the Norfolk area and threatened the Gosport Navy Yard in Portsmouth.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The commandant there, Captain Charles S.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] McCauley, though loyal to the Union, was immobilized by advice he received from his subordinate officers, most of whom were in favor of secession.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Although he had orders from (Union) Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles to move his ships to Northern ports, he refused to act until April 20, when he gave orders to scuttle the ships in the yard and destroy its facilities.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] At least nine ships were burned, among them the screw frigate USS *Merrimack*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Merrimack* burned only to the waterline, however, and her engines were more or less intact.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The destruction of the navy yard was mostly ineffective; in particular, the large drydock there was relatively undamaged and soon could be restored.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Without firing a shot, the advocates of secession had gained for the South its largest navy yard, as well as the hull and engines of what would be in time its most famous warship.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] They had also seized more than a thousand heavy guns, plus gun carriages and large quantities of gunpowder.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Norfolk and its navy yard in Portsmouth, the Confederacy controlled the southern side of Hampton Roads.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] To prevent Union warships from attacking the yard, the Confederates set up batteries at Sewell's Point and Craney Island, at the juncture of the Elizabeth River with the James.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] (See map.) The Union retained possession of Fort Monroe, at Old Point Comfort on the Virginia Peninsula.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] They also held a small man-made island known as the Rip Raps, on the far side of the channel opposite Fort Monroe, and on this island they completed another fort, named Fort Wool.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] With Fort Monroe went control of the lower Peninsula as far as Newport News.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Forts Monroe and Wool gave the Union forces control of the entrance to Hampton Roads.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The blockade, initiated on April 30, 1861, cut off Norfolk and Richmond from the sea almost completely.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] To further the blockade, the Union Navy stationed some of its most powerful warships in the roadstead.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] There, they were under the shelter of the shore-based guns of Fort Monroe and the batteries at Hampton and Newport News and out of the range of the guns at Sewell's Point and Craney Island.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] For most of the first year of the war, the Confederacy could do little to oppose or dislodge them.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] When steam propulsion began to be applied to warships, naval constructors renewed their interest in armor for their vessels.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Experiments had been tried with armor during the Crimean War (1853–1856), just prior to the American Civil War, and the British and French navies had each built armored ships and were planning to build others.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] In 1860 the French Navy commissioned *La Gloire*, the world's first ocean-going ironclad warship.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Great Britain followed a year later with HMS *Warrior*, the world's first armor-plated iron-hulled warship.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The use of armor remained controversial, however, and the United States Navy was generally reluctant to embrace the new technology.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] When the Civil War broke out in 1861, Confederate Secretary of the Navy Stephen R.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory was an early enthusiast for the advantages of armor.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] As he looked upon it, the Confederacy could not match the industrial North in numbers of ships at sea, so they would have to compete by building vessels that individually outclassed those of the Union.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory gathered about himself a group of men who could put his vision into practice, among them John M.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] When Mallory's men searched the South for factories that could build engines to drive the heavy ships that he wanted, they found no place to do it immediately.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] At the best facility, the Tredegar Iron Works in Richmond, building engines from scratch would take at least a year.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Upon learning this, Williamson suggested taking the engines from the hulk of *Merrimack*, recently raised from the bed of the Elizabeth River.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] His colleagues promptly accepted his suggestion and expanded it, proposing that the design of their projected ironclad be adapted to the hull.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Porter produced the revised plans, which were submitted to Mallory for approval.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On July 11, 1861, the new design was accepted, and work began almost immediately.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The burned-out hull was towed into the graving dock that the Union Navy had failed to destroy.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] During the subsequent conversion process, the plans developed further, incorporating an iron ram fitted to the prow.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The re-modeled ship's offense, in addition to the ram, consisted of 10 guns: six 9 in (230 mm) smooth-bore Dahlgrens, two 6.4 in (160 mm) and two 7 in (180 mm) Brooke rifles.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Trials showed that these rifles firing solid shot would pierce up to eight inches of armor plating.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Tredegar Iron works could produce both solid shot and shell, and since it was believed that *Virginia* would face only wooden ships, she was given only the explosive shell.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor plating, originally meant to be 1 in (25 mm) thick, was replaced by double plates, each 2 in (51 mm) thick, backed by 24 in (61 cm) of iron and pine.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The armor was pierced for 14 gunports: four on each broadside, three forward, and three aft.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The revisions, together with the usual problems associated with the transportation system of the South, resulted in delays that pushed out the launch date until February 3, 1862, and she was not commissioned until February 17, bearing the name CSS *Virginia*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Intelligence that the Confederates were working to develop an ironclad caused consternation for the Union, but Secretary of the Navy Gideon Welles waited for Congress to meet to request permission to consider building armored vessels; Congress gave this permission on August 3, 1861.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Welles appointed a commission, which became known as the Ironclad Board, of three senior naval officers to choose among the designs that were submitted for consideration.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The three men were Captains Joseph Smith, Hiram Paulding, and Commander Charles Henry Davis.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The board considered seventeen designs, and chose to support three.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The first of the three to be completed, even though she was by far the most radical in design, was Swedish engineer and inventor John Ericsson's USS *Monitor*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson's *Monitor*, which was built at Ericsson's yard on the East River in Greenpoint, Brooklyn, incorporated new and striking design features, the most significant of which were her armor and armament.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Instead of the large numbers of guns of rather small bore that had characterized warships in the past, Ericsson opted for only two guns of large caliber; he wanted to use 15 in (380 mm) guns, but had to settle for 11 in (280 mm) Dahlgren guns when the larger size were unavailable.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] These were mounted in a cylindrical turret, 20 ft (6.1 m) in diameter, 9 ft (2.7 m) high, covered with iron 8 in (200 mm) thick.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The whole rotated on a central spindle, and was moved by a steam engine that could be controlled by one man.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ericsson was afraid that using the full 30 pounds of black powder to fire the huge cannon would raise the risk of an explosion in the turret.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] He demanded that a charge of 15 pounds be used to lessen this possibility.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] As with *Virginia*, trials found that a full charge would pierce armor plate, a finding that would have affected the outcome of the battle.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] A serious flaw in the design was the pilot house from which the ship would be conned, a small structure forward of the turret on the main deck.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Its presence meant that the guns could not fire directly forward, and it was isolated from other activities on the ship.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Despite the late start and the novelty of construction, *Monitor* was actually completed a few days before her counterpart *Virginia*, but the Confederates activated *Virginia* first.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The Confederate chain of command was anomalous.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lieutenant Catesby ap Roger Jones had directed much of the conversion of *Merrimack* to *Virginia*, and he was disappointed when he was not named her captain.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Jones was retained aboard *Virginia*, but only as her executive officer.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Ordinarily, the ship would have been led by a captain of the Confederate States Navy, to be determined by the rigid seniority system that was in place.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Secretary Mallory wanted the aggressive Franklin Buchanan, but at least two other captains had greater seniority and had applied for the post.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Mallory evaded the issue by appointing Buchanan, head of the Office of Orders and Detail, flag officer in charge of the defenses of Norfolk and the James River.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] As such, he could control the movements of *Virginia*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Technically, therefore, the ship went into the battle without a captain.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the Union side, command of the North Atlantic Blockading Squadron was held by Flag Officer Louis M.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] He had devised a plan for his frigates to engage *Virginia*, hoping to trap her in their crossfire.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] In the event, his plan broke down completely when four of the ships ran aground (one of them intentionally) in the confined waters of the roadstead.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] On the day of battle, Goldsborough was absent with the ships cooperating with the Burnside Expedition in North Carolina.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] In his absence, leadership fell to his second in command, Captain John Marston of USS *Roanoke*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] As *Roanoke* was one of the ships that ran aground, Marston was unable to materially influence the battle, and his participation is often disregarded.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Most accounts emphasize the contribution of the captain of *Monitor*, John L.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Marston did, however, disregard orders from Secretary of War Gideon Welles to send the *Monitor* back to Washington, D.C., ahead of the battle, ensuring that it would be present to confront the *Merrimack*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The battle began when the large and unwieldy CSS *Virginia* steamed into Hampton Roads on the morning of March 8, 1862.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Captain Buchanan intended to attack as soon as possible.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] *Virginia* was accompanied from her moorings on the Elizabeth River by *Raleigh* and *Beaufort*, and was joined at Hampton Roads by the James River Squadron, *Patrick Henry*, *Jamestown*, and *Teaser*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] When they were passing the Union batteries at Newport News, *Patrick Henry* was temporarily disabled by a shot in her boiler that killed four of her crew.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] After repairs, she returned and rejoined the others.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] At this time, the Union Navy had five warships in the roadstead, in addition to several support vessels.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The sloop-of-war *Cumberland* and frigate *Congress* were anchored in the channel near Newport News.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] Lawrence* and the steam frigates *Roanoke* and *Minnesota* were near Fort Monroe, along with the storeship *Brandywine*.
[src:css-virginia/battle-of-hampton-roads] The latter three got under way as soon as they saw *Virginia* approaching, but all soon ran aground.
